`useStore` (`src/lib/store.ts:31`) hands every subscriber the **entire** state object via `useSyncExternalStore`. Every `store.set()` call creates a brand-new top-level object (`{...s, [bookId]: ...}` in `progress.ts:39`), so **every** component calling `useAllProgress()` or `useBookProgress()` re-renders on **any** book's progress change — not just the one that changed.

Concretely: `Library.tsx:30` calls `useAllProgress()` inside `BookCard`, once per card. Marking one chapter as read in *any* book re-renders *every* `BookCard` on the library page (could be dozens), each of which also recomputes `bookStats(book)` (see #3).

```tsx
// src/pages/Library.tsx — current
function BookCard({ book, step }: { book: Book; step?: number }) {
  const all = useAllProgress()       // subscribes to the WHOLE store
  const progress = all[book.id]
  ...
}
```

**Fix:** add a selector-based subscription to `store.ts` so components only re-render when their slice actually changes:

```ts
// src/lib/store.ts
export function useStoreSelector<T extends object, S>(
  store: Store<T>,
  selector: (s: T) => S,
): S {
  return useSyncExternalStore(
    store.subscribe,
    () => selector(store.get()),
    () => selector(store.get()),
  )
}
```

```ts
// src/lib/progress.ts
export function useBookProgress(bookId: string): BookProgress {
  return useStoreSelector(store, (all) => sanitize(all[bookId]))
}
```

`useStoreSelector` still returns a fresh object each call (since `sanitize` builds a new object), so pair it with `useSyncExternalStoreWithSelector` (from `use-sync-external-store/shim/with-selector`) or a shallow-equal memo if you want true skip-on-unrelated-change behavior — plain `useSyncExternalStore` will still re-render on every store write because the selector result is a new reference. The `with-selector` variant does the equality check for you.

`getBook`, `booksInCategory`, and `categoryOf` all do `.find()`/`.filter()` over the full `books`/`categories` arrays, and are called on **every render** of `BookMap.tsx` (lines 75, 104, 107) and `Reader.tsx` (line 24) — not just once. With a bigger catalog this is the closest thing to an N+1 pattern here: repeated O(n) scans that should be O(1) map lookups, since `books`/`categories` are static after module load.

```ts
// src/lib/content.ts — add alongside the existing arrays
const booksById = new Map(books.map((b) => [b.id, b]))
const categoriesById = new Map(categories.map((c) => [c.id, c]))
const booksByCategoryId = new Map<string, Book[]>()
for (const b of books) {
  const list = booksByCategoryId.get(b.categoryId) ?? []
  list.push(b)
  booksByCategoryId.set(b.categoryId, list)
}

export function getBook(id: string | undefined): Book | undefined {
  return id ? booksById.get(id) : undefined
}
export function booksInCategory(categoryId: string): Book[] {
  return booksByCategoryId.get(categoryId) ?? []
}
export function categoryOf(book: Book): Category | undefined {
  return categoriesById.get(book.categoryId)
}
```

`bookStats(book)` (`content.ts:154`) does two `countWords`/regex passes over every chapter summary. It's pure — given `books` is static — yet `Library.tsx:32` recomputes it inside every `BookCard` render, and `Library.tsx:111` recomputes it again for `totals` (that one is at least memoized with `useMemo([])`).

**Fix — memoize once per book at module load:**

```ts
// src/lib/content.ts
const statsCache = new Map<string, BookStats>()
export function bookStats(b: Book): BookStats {
  let s = statsCache.get(b.id)
  if (!s) {
    s = computeBookStats(b)   // rename current function body
    statsCache.set(b.id, s)
  }
  return s
}
```

`content.ts:173-193` recomputes `strong`/`mid`/`weak` lowercase strings (including a `categoryOf` lookup and joining every chapter title) for **every book, on every keystroke** in `Library.tsx`'s search box. None of this depends on the query — only scoring does.

**Fix — precompute the searchable corpus once:**

```ts
// src/lib/content.ts
const searchCorpus = books.map((b) => ({
  b,
  strong: `${b.title} ${b.author}`.toLowerCase(),
  mid: `${b.tagline} ${categoryOf(b)?.name ?? ''}`.toLowerCase(),
  weak: b.map.chapters.map((c) => c.title).join(' ').toLowerCase(),
}))

export function searchBooks(query: string): Book[] {
  const q = query.trim().toLowerCase()
  if (!q) return books
  const terms = q.split(/\s+/)
  return searchCorpus
    .map(({ b, strong, mid, weak }) => {
      let score = 0
      for (const t of terms) {
        if (strong.includes(t)) score += 5
        if (mid.includes(t)) score += 2
        if (weak.includes(t)) score += 1
      }
      return { b, score }
    })
    .filter((x) => x.score > 0)
    .sort((x, y) => y.score - x.score)
    .map((x) => x.b)
}
```

`Reader.tsx:64` calls `loadChapter(bookId, n)` in a `useEffect` on every `[bookId, n]` change with no cache — so navigating back to a previously-viewed chapter re-runs the title/section regex splits and `mdToHtml` (a full `marked.parse`) again. Chapter files never change at runtime.

```ts
// src/lib/content.ts
const chapterCache = new Map<string, Chapter | null>()
export async function loadChapter(bookId: string, n: number): Promise<Chapter | null> {
  const key = `${bookId}:${n}`
  if (chapterCache.has(key)) return chapterCache.get(key)!
  const loader = chapterIndex.get(bookId)?.get(n)
  if (!loader) { chapterCache.set(key, null); return null }
  const chapter = await buildChapter(bookId, n, await loader())  // extract current body into buildChapter
  chapterCache.set(key, chapter)
  return chapter
}
```

This also fixes a subtle UX/perf issue: rapid prev/next navigation currently triggers a fresh async parse + a loading flash every time, even for chapters already visited this session.

